7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 547, L.D. 861, “An Act Related to the
10 Work of the Public Advocate”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'An Act to Prohibit the Public Advocate and a Commissioner of the Public Utilities
13 Commission from Certain Employment Activities Following Service'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
15 following:
16 'Sec. 1. 35-A MRSA §124 is enacted to read:
17 §124. Post-term employment restrictions; commissioners
18 1. Definition. As used in this section, "employment" means any full-time or part-time
19 work performed for compensation and includes, but is not limited to, consulting and
20 membership on a board.
21 2. Prohibitions. An individual serving as a commissioner on or appointed to serve as
22 a commissioner on or after December 15, 2025 may not, until 12 months after the
23 completion of the commissioner's service in accordance with section 105, subsection 2:
24 A. Solicit employment with or accept employment from a public utility in the State; or
25 B. Appear before the commission for compensation in a commission proceeding on
26 behalf of a person.
27 3. Penalties. An individual who violates this section is subject to a civil penalty not to
28 exceed $1,000 per occurrence, payable to the State.
29 4. Enforcement. The Office of the Attorney General may investigate alleged violations
30 of this section and bring an action for a violation of this section.
31 Sec. 2. 35-A MRSA §1715 is enacted to read:
32 §1715. Post-term employment restrictions
Page 1 - 132LR2150(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 547, L.D. 861
1 1. Definition. As used in this section, "employment" means any full-time or part-time
2 work performed for compensation and includes, but is not limited to, consulting and
3 membership on a board.
4 2. Certain employment prohibited. An individual serving as the Public Advocate on
5 or appointed to serve as the Public Advocate on or after December 15, 2025 may not, until
6 12 months after the completion of the Public Advocate's service in accordance with section
7 1701, subsection 1-A:
8 A. Solicit employment with or accept employment from a public utility in the State; or
9 B. Appear before the commission for compensation in a commission proceeding on
10 behalf of a person, other than a state agency or quasi-independent state entity, if that
11 person was a party to an adjudicatory proceeding in which the Public Advocate was a
12 party during the Public Advocate's term of service.
13 3. Penalties. An individual who violates this section is subject to a civil penalty not to
14 exceed $1,000 per occurrence, payable to the State.
15 4. Enforcement. The Office of the Attorney General may investigate alleged violations
16 of this section and bring an action for a violation of this section.'
17 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
18 number to read consecutively.
19 SUMMARY
2200 This amendment replaces the bill, which is a concept draft, and changes the title. It
2211 prohibits the Public Advocate or a commissioner of the Public Utilities Commission
2222 serving on or appointed on or after December 15, 2025, until 12 months after the
2233 completion of the Public Advocate's or commissioner's service, from soliciting or accepting
2244 employment from a public utility. It also prohibits, until 12 months after the completion of
2255 service, a commissioner from appearing before the commission in a proceeding for
2266 compensation and the Public Advocate from appearing before the commission in a
2277 proceeding for compensation on behalf of a person, other than a state agency or quasi-
2288 independent state entity, if that person was a party to an adjudicatory proceeding in which
2299 the Public Advocate was a party during the Public Advocate's term of service. The
3300 amendment provides that the law is enforced by the Office of the Attorney General and an
3311 individual who violates the law is subject to a civil penalty not to exceed $1,000 per
3322 occurrence.
